00:08:48.320 --> 00:08:52.630
of Shakespeare's plays, in
the new re-opened theatres.

00:08:52.630 --> 00:08:56.360
For example, Dryden's adaptations
of the Tempest and Anthony

00:08:56.360 --> 00:09:00.000
and Cleopatra and this
was the historical moment,

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:03.530
when Shakespeare was to
adapt Ben Johnson's tribute,

00:09:03.530 --> 00:09:08.300
in his dedicatory poem, in the
folio, suddenly seen as not

00:09:08.300 --> 00:09:12.020
for all time but rather of age.

00:09:12.020 --> 00:09:14.620
Dramatists felt it was
necessary to drag Shakespeare

00:09:14.620 --> 00:09:17.840
into the second half of
the seventeenth-century.

00:09:17.840 --> 00:09:22.510
So this is when we had most famous
example, Mahem Tates adaptation

00:09:22.510 --> 00:09:28.120
of King Lear 1681, and which
alongside many other alterations

00:09:28.120 --> 00:09:30.800
by a happy ending.

00:09:30.800 --> 00:09:32.760
Tates version of Lear had
dominated the stage for much

00:09:32.760 --> 00:09:38.290
of the eighteenth century, although
it too was altered in various ways.

00:09:38.290 --> 00:09:41.490
The editing of Shakespeare in the
eighteenth century was inspired

00:09:41.490 --> 00:09:45.560
by similar ideas, which was that
Shakespeare was certainly a genius,

00:09:45.560 --> 00:09:49.570
but he was an antiquated one, who
had to be approved by an editor,

00:09:49.570 --> 00:09:50.910
in order to be comprehensible.

00:09:50.910 --> 00:09:55.070
The eighteenth century was when
Shakespeare began to be edited

00:09:55.070 --> 00:09:59.060
in a way that we might
recognize as modern editing.

00:09:59.060 --> 00:10:01.730
His language and punctuation
were modernized,

00:10:01.730 --> 00:10:04.640
editors annotated passages
that needed explaining

00:10:04.640 --> 00:10:09.400 position:56%
and they changed words and phrases,
that they considered to be mistakes,

00:10:09.400 --> 00:10:11.880
whether the mistakes were
made by early printers

00:10:11.880 --> 00:10:15.270
or possibly even by
Shakespeare himself.

00:10:15.270 --> 00:10:18.220
Unfortunately, from the
very beginning editing seems

00:10:18.220 --> 00:10:22.040
to have gone hand-in-hand with
mean minded bad-tempered rivalry

00:10:22.040 --> 00:10:24.660
between editors, something
I'm afraid to say,

00:10:24.660 --> 00:10:26.530
that continues to this very day.

00:10:26.530 --> 00:10:28.390
Setting that aside,

00:10:28.390 --> 00:10:32.070
in the eighteenth century there
were great editors of Shakespeare,

00:10:32.070 --> 00:10:34.930
but they didn't really
produce great additions.

00:10:34.930 --> 00:10:39.360
In 1709 with the publication
of the collected edition,

00:10:39.360 --> 00:10:43.850 position:56%
edited by Nichols Road and published
by Jacob Thompson, whose firm was

00:10:43.850 --> 00:10:48.650
to maintain a tight hole on
Shakespeare during the century.

00:10:48.650 --> 00:10:52.350
the structure of collected
Shakespeare additions was set

00:10:52.350 --> 00:10:55.790
in a format that perseveres
to the present day.

00:10:55.790 --> 00:10:59.720
This six-volume edition begins
with a biography of Shakespeare,

00:10:59.720 --> 00:11:03.090
with Road excusing this with
the formula that was also

00:11:03.090 --> 00:11:06.230
to become common during
the period, He says.

00:11:06.230 --> 00:11:09.560
Though the works of Mr. Shakespeare
may seem to many not to want

00:11:09.560 --> 00:11:13.540
to comment, yet, I fancy some
little account of the man himself,

00:11:13.540 --> 00:11:17.300
may not be thought improper,
to go along with them.

00:11:17.300 --> 00:11:20.750
His hesitation of the biographical
details and the necessity

00:11:20.750 --> 00:11:24.040
of them was to shift
quite dramatically.

00:11:24.040 --> 00:11:27.710
So that by the nineteenth century
every possible biographical tidbit,

00:11:27.710 --> 00:11:30.470
related to Shakespeare was
treated with reference.

00:11:30.470 --> 00:11:33.460
Including many that were
of doubtful veracity.

00:11:33.460 --> 00:11:36.910 position:56%
Road, also established a practice
of regularization of things like act

00:11:36.910 --> 00:11:41.580
and scene divisions, as well
as standardized cast lists

00:11:41.580 --> 00:11:44.280
at the beginning of the play,
along with the modernization

00:11:44.280 --> 00:11:46.730
of spelling and punctuation.

00:11:46.730 --> 00:11:49.180
Road based his texts
on the forth folio

00:11:49.180 --> 00:11:52.610
and again he set a
precedent whereby most

00:11:52.610 --> 00:11:55.200 position:56%
of the succeeding eighteenth-century
traditions,

00:11:55.200 --> 00:11:58.450
